    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Bassett, Southampton</placeName>
                    <date>Sept. 1. 75</date>
                    <salute>Dear D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Fayrer</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very much obliged for your present just received.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I have always felt a strange interest about the Tiger &amp; shall be very glad to read your book.— Thanks for your offer of assistance in India, but I have at present no enquiry to make.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Your expedition with the Prince will be I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. think most interesting &amp; splendid.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Pray believe me | Yours very faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 Southampton] <hi rend="italic">before del</hi> ‘<hi rend="italic">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>’ </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">There is a copy of Fayrer’s <hi rend="italic">The royal tiger of Bengal</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8594.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Fayrer 1875</ref>) in the Darwin Library–Down.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10142.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Joseph Fayrer, 31 August 1875</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Fayrer was planning to go to India with Albert Edward, the prince of Wales (the future King Edward VII).</note>
        </div>        
            
